segments.text: This was, I think, about the first week of March.
And I never saw anybody from the second hurdle on.
And it was very pleasant.
All right.
Then Texas Relays, I guess, that was a big meet in those days, wasn't it?
It was the biggest meet.
It was the first outdoor meet in the country.
Oh.
And it was...
always on the second weekend of April.
And all the big schools from up north would come down because that would give them a chance to run outdoors for the first time.
And the Midwestern schools were very powerful in those days, Oklahoma, Oklahoma.
And Minnesota, Michigan, Notre Dame, they'd come down.
And a lot of the smaller schools that were big in track would come down as well.
And they had a lot of distance people.
And they would come down and compete.
And that was my first big meet.
In fact, that was, well, no, I take it back.
The first big meet was the Fort Worth Fat Stock Show meet.
at Farrington Field in mid-March.
And we did quite well.
We had a powerful freshman track team that year.
And we wiped everybody out.
And we had powerful hurdlers, powerful sprinters, powerful relay teams.
and we were pretty good in the field events too.
We had a good high jumper, Don Graves from Brownwood.
Weight men, we were a little shy.
Colonel Landy didn't recruit weight men that year because he still had George Cadera for another two years.
I guess that's why he didn't recruit any weight men until he recruited Darragh Hooper the following year.
Right, and then at the Texas Relays, you went over there?
I won there.
I won the high hurdles and set a new freshman record.
And that trophy up there came from the Texas Relays.
How good.
Clyde Littlefield presented it with tight jaws, I might add.
Remember what the time was?
Yeah, I think it was...
And how did that compare with the varsity times?
Varsity times were 14-6.
So you were right.
All right, then any other big meets before the conference meet?
No, we didn't.
Freshmen didn't have a conference meet.
Oh, you didn't?
Oh, really?
No.
We ran against Texas and Rice Fish.
We'd have a triangular meet, and that was a conference meet because there wasn't anybody else that had a powerful fish team in the conference then.
Did you lose any of the high hurdles that year?
No, I was undefeated in both hurdles that year.
So how did you feel athletically when you finished that spring as competition?
I felt good.
Did you have any goals you hadn't reached?
Goal setting hadn't been invented then.
Okay.
Like you hear today.
And I had no particular goals except just to do the best that I could.
What did you eat or drink or not eat or drink?
Or what were your diet and behavior rules for yourself?
I had none, just don't overload myself on the day of a meet.
And always try to have a bowel movement so that I'd be a couple of pounds lighter.
And not eat just right before.
Did you drink soft drinks and eat ice cream and malts or anything?
Oh yes, sure.
And there were no vitamin additives then, were there?
They were available, but nobody took them.
Steroids hadn't been invented.
Herbal supplements were something that you fed the rabbits and goats.
No, things were very simple then.
And you weighed, what did you weigh then?
I weighed 172 pounds.
And you're what, 6'1"?
I was 6'1".
Okay.
So as that spring is ending, has your wife moved up to College Station yet?
Not yet.
Okay.
She would come up and the Andersons would move out of their master suite into Rusty's bedroom and Rusty would bunk with Wally.
at 501 Fairview, and as a matter of fact, we spent our honeymoon in the Anderson's Master Suite that whole week.
Think how, by today's rules, that would probably be some NCAA violation that the coach provided.
That would be putting it mildly.
I can foresee losing 10 scholarships,
never being able to participate in the NCAA meet, all kinds of bad things like that.
Now, do you remember what your best time was that spring?
Yes.
It was 14-5 in the high hurdles, which beat the Southwest Conference time that year, and 22-9 in the low hurdles, which broke the Southwest Conference record.
And let's see, in high school, was it 200 yard?
200 yards.
But in the college, was it 220?
But it was 110 in both the highs.
120 in both.
120 in both.
We ran yards.
Oh, yeah, yeah.
I'm sorry.
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
Okay, so as you go home, as school is out that spring, how did you feel about that first year?
I felt very good about it.
I'd had a great time.
I had done far better than I ever anticipated.
My folks were ecstatic with my grades.
Colonel Landy, I might add, was a little proud as well.
And I was inducted into Phi Eta Sigma, an honorary scholastic fraternity.
The Beaumont A&M Club was also quite proud.
Did anybody... Charlie Babcock was proud.
Did anybody ever come up to you that year or any other year and try to hand you some money on the side or anything that would have been inappropriate?
I'm surprised you would ask that.
You ever hear of the Coconose Brothers?
Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.
Beaumont.
That's C-O-K-I-N-O-S. That's right.
There were four brothers, Genos, Jimmy, Mike, and Andy.
They spent a lot of time on campus, particularly during football season.
Jimmy would always come up with his cronies, and they'd stay, I don't know, someplace.
And mysteriously,
a black Ford would appear in the parking lot behind Hart Hall.
And mysteriously, an envelope would appear under my door that would say, the key to that car is under the floor mat.
And be sure and look in the glove compartment.
And I would look in the glove compartment and there would be an envelope with a $20 bill in it.
And boy, a $20 bill would go a long way in College Station.
And frequently, my bride to be would get a ride of Jimmy for the football season, if my folks weren't coming.
But no, other than that, when I'd go home, of course, I couldn't buy
I couldn't buy a meal when I'd go out.
Charlie Meyer was the High Sheriff of Jefferson County.
He'd always insist that you come down to see him on Christmas Eve and you'd go down there and he'd slap a pint of Old Crow in your hand.
It was a different era.
What did you do that first summer?
I went to work for Trotty and Thompson Construction Company, a couple of Aggies, Jess Thompson and Bill Trotty.
They were late 20s, early 30s vintage.
And they had a road construction company there in Beaumont.
They did city streets and farm to market roads.
And Ben Ramsey was the lieutenant governor at that time, and Ben Ramsey would make sure that
Farmer Market Roads always got on the legislative agenda, since he said it was the Lieutenant Governor, and Trotty and Thompson got their share of contracts.
It did not hurt that Trotty and Thompson was an informal subsidiary of Brown and Rupp, and I hired on with Trotty and Thompson and worked roads, dug ditches,
menial labor until they found out that I could drive a truck.
And then I drove a truck and did menial labor.
And then I drove a tanker truck, a water truck for them and worked for them every summer for four years.
All right, then in the fall of 49, coming back for your sophomore year, you're staying in business as a major.
That's right.
Do you remember what it was officially titled?
Was it called Business or Business Administration?
It was called the Department of Business Administration.
Okay.
And did your wife come with you then?
Yes.
And where did you all live?
We lived... We lived there.
It was 16...
16 by 16 foot hut, it was called.
You may have seen pictures of the drill field in World War I, how they had these shacks all around the drill field.
And that's what that was.
And Colonel Andy bought one of those and moved it to his property for use as a servant's quarters.
And this was on the back of the...
The back of their house.
And they lived on the south side of the campus?
on the south side of the campus at 501 Fairview, which was about four blocks from South Side Grocery, which is where Rother's bookstore is now.
Yeah, yeah.
And you paid rent?
No.
Okay.
No rent.
All right, what did your, did your wife have a job or did she stay home?
No, she stayed home.
There were just no jobs available.
All right.
You still were in the Corps officially.
Oh, absolutely.
And so you wore your uniforms.
Every day.
Describe your routine then as a young married man going to Texas A&M.
I would ride my bicycle to the first class.
If I felt like it, I would stop at Sabisa and have breakfast so my wife wouldn't have to get up and cook.
We had an old Detroit Jewel, Detroit Jewel it's called, gas stove.
And incidentally, we had to put an extra gas line out there to put in a water heater.
That place did not have hot water.
So my father-in-law and my dad,
brought a hot water heater up one day used and we put that sucker in and we had hot water and we washed dishes in the bathtub.
But I would go to my first class on a bicycle and most of the classes were down in the in the shacks they were called.
And those were at Northgate?
No, those were
where the water tower is now.
Yeah, yeah.
I mean, on the north side of the campus.
On the north side of the campus, yeah.
And they were World War II leftover prefabs?
They were World War II barracks buildings.
Oh, barracks, okay.
That had been partitioned into classrooms.
Drafty and cold, if you wouldn't believe.
Now, in 49, were freshmen back on the campus?
No.
They're still?
They're still out at Bryan Annex.
But the campus was crowded.
because of the veterans.
That's right.
We still had a lot of veterans.
But they were starting to dwindle off.
The class of 50 was the largest class that had come through.
I think class of 50 had 1,500 students in it.
We had about 1,250 in our class of 52.
What did you young kids think about those old World War II veterans?
We were in awe.
They didn't talk much about it.
They didn't particularly want to.
Particularly those who had been in combat.
Now those who had not been in combat would open up more and tell you what barracks life was like and this kind of business.
But we didn't bug them because
We'd leave them alone.
But we had a number of veterans in our classes.
That bicycle that you rode to the campus, you never locked it, did you?
No.
And would you sometimes... Never thought about it.
Yeah.
Did you sometimes take from class to class or did you leave it at Sebesa?
Well, I'd leave it at Sebesa.
I took it with me from
Every building.
And did you come back and eat lunch on campus or go home?
I'd come back and eat lunch at Sbisa.
And your degree plan was set up so that you would graduate in four years.
Oh, yes, sir.
Everybody's was.
Today's kids cannot believe it.
You took 19 hours?
My goodness.
How could you handle that many?
Well, engineering students had more than that.
That's right.
And the students just cannot believe that.
Did you go home to eat lunch or eat on campus?
I ate at Sabisa.
At Sabisa.
And then in the fall, you're a sophomore, junior, and seniors.
You're still working out cross-country.
We'd go to that cross-country course and sprain our ankles.
Colonel Andy let us get by with three days a week.
But then of course up popped the Sugar Bowl meet.
Sugar Bowl had a track meet.
I don't know if you do that.
Yeah, I remember that.
But those of us who were invited to the Sugar Bowl meet would have to start a pretty strenuous workout schedule in November and December.
all the way through the Christmas holidays.
And that got to be a pain.
I mean, it was an honor to be invited to run in Sugar Bowl meet, but we had other things that we wanted to do.
But we showed up, and we gave a good account of ourself.
I was running against the West Coast record holder.
And I came in second in the higher.
Didn't have it lower.
In those days, for meets like that, did you get a ribbon or a medal?
What were the symbols of victory?
For the larger meets, a medal.
For the triangular meets and that sort of thing, you get a pat on the back.
What about conference meets?
Conference meets?
First three places got medals.
And even after they went to scoring five and six places, it was still first three places got medals.
And so as you and your wife are settling in to being a married couple, what did you all do at night?
We'd listen to the radio.
We would play Canasta with Wally and Rusty Anderson.

If you got your freshman numeral, which meant you lettered as a freshman, because freshmen were not varsity eligible in those days, you also got 20 tickets, free tickets, to Guyon Hall, which is where movies were shown on cameras.
And there were...
various and sundry other perquisites that one came by surreptitiously.
What was it like to go to a Gien Hall movie?
How did the Aggies conduct themselves in there?
Oh, well, when a pretty girl would come on the screen, you know, the whistles.
But they were a pretty orderly bunch.
And you could get old-fashioned popcorn and all that there.
You could get popcorn and no gum.
They didn't want it on their seats.
Where else did a young couple go in the evenings if you wanted?
You could go to a campus movie, which is where something Canyon, Shadow Canyon I think is now.
And we didn't have any money.
And if we did have money, there was no place to go.
We'd play bridge.
We'd go over to other couples' houses.
A pretty simple life.
A big weekend was when you'd get your $10 a month laundry check, and you'd find somebody, some other couple who had a car, and you would go down to the Triangle Drive Inn,
which is where Chicken Oil Company is now.
And you'd get a big, juicy hamburger on a giant elephant ear bun.
And that was really living it up.
You could get a hamburger for 50 cents and a huge Coke for two bits.
Now, if a couple, whether it be y'all or anyone else, if a young couple wanted to do something pretty wild,
What possibilities were there in Brazos County?
I don't know where you'd do it.
I'm not sure what you mean by why.
Was there a place that a person could get legally or otherwise alcoholic beverages?
Not legally, but you could get it.
Whiskey Bridge was the closest place.
And the old stone statues are still there to this day.
The bridge has been dismantled, I guess sold for scrap.
But you'd just go across Whiskey Bridge and get a half pint, or a pint was the most anybody could afford.
And you'd have to make that last.
Now, was Uncle Ed's operating in that era?
Uncle Ed's was operating in, of course, I never took my wife out to Uncle Ed's.
I don't know of anybody that took a date out to Uncle Ed's either.
We'd just go out there for good bull and
a couple of beers.
Now, beer was legal, wasn't it?
In Brassets County.
Brassets County, that's what I mean, yeah.
Was there a boot, nobody that I've asked this question of has had an answer that yes, they did.
Did you ever hear of a bootlegger in Brassets County?
Never did.
And there was no House of Ill Repute in Brassets County, was there?
I never heard anybody mention one.
Brenham, I think, was the closest place.
Now, was the chicken ranch, did you guys know about the chicken ranch?
Oh, yeah.
Is that right?
The chicken ranch was alive and well.
Did Aggies really go over to the chicken ranch?
Absolutely.
Was there any kind of a ritual that a fish was supposed to go or anything like that?
I suppose there might have been.
I wasn't aware of it.
Fish didn't go, I guess for a couple of reasons.
They didn't have a car.
They didn't have any money.
The upperclassmen had cars and usually a little more money.
And I don't know, maybe they'd get together a car load once a semester or something like that and go.
Now there was no organized activity on the campus for married students, was there?
There was no... No.
Hey, honey.
There were no scheduled activities specifically for married couples, were there?
Student married couples?
Oh, I think there may have been some music groups, bridge groups, something like that.
We had a bowling alley in the basement of the Y, but I think there were two alleys or something.
You just didn't get a whole lot of people down there.
Was Mr. Cashin still active in those days?
Which Cashin are you talking about?
Red and Jim's dad.
I did not know Mr. Cashin.
Okay.
He's the one that created the Y, and I don't know when he died.
Mrs. Cashin, she ended up being the lady that ran the big board of directors house on the north side of Sabeasa.
After he died, she was the lady responsible for operating it.
I remember the house, but I do not remember Jesus Cash.
What about religious groups?
Were you all churchgoers then?
Occasionally.
There were a number of religious groups for all religions here.
There was the Hillel Society for the Jewish students, and they were very active.
There were Protestant men in the chapel.
Each of the local churches sponsored a youth activity group that was geared towards students.
Do you remember Religious Emphasis Week in the spring?
I remember the name, I remember it happening, but I was usually too involved off on a track trip someplace to be able to participate.
But we weren't really churchy.
Describe the student body during your four years here.
Describe the student body in general.
Where were they from?
What kinds of family backgrounds, their attitudes, their ancestry, et cetera?
The majority of the student body was WASP, white, Anglo-Saxon, Protestant.
We had just a smattering of Hispanics.
A few Jewish students, Aaron Cohen, a classmate of mine.
Aaron made a tremendous name for himself at the Johnson Space Center.
How were Jewish students treated by the other students?
Just like everybody else.
Not a bit of difference.
Same for the Hispanic students.
They were just part of the gang.
Were there any international students that you remember?
There were, but they were mostly graduate students and we didn't have a lot of contact with them.
They were mostly in engineering and agriculture.
And there were almost no Asian students in those days, were there?
Not then.
That's what I thought.
There were Latin American students,

no i don't recall any european students don't recall any canadian students but there were there were there was a rare asiatic student now there were a bunch of catholic kids oh yeah german czech polish you bet uh hometown clubs were still going big then hometown clubs were big what were they why were make believe i didn't know why they existed well uh
Because you got to get back with your own kind and talk about, hey, who's going with Susie now that she's off at TSCW, that kind of thing.
And who's got an extra seat in the car going home this week?
Who's going home?
You kept book on who's going home in the car.
Did you ever hitchhike as an Aggie?
Frequently.
Frequently.
make believe I'd never heard of that.
Describe how an Aggie hitchhiked.
Well, at Eastgate, there was what was called the Aggie Line.
And the first freshman to show up would be elected.
Well, he wasn't elected.
He was told to go out there and stand and stick out his thumb for a ride.
We always hitchhiked in uniform.
And in those days, it was easy to hitchhike.
And people who came back and forth on Highway 6 knew Aggies and they would always stop to pick them up.
The drill was that the freshman who was standing out there with his thumb out, when the car stopped, he'd say, yes sir, where are you going and how many people can you take?
The driver would tell him and he'd holler back and say, two going to Houston.
The first two guys in line who were going to Houston pick up their
go to hell bag and run out there and get in the car.
And some of us had these little tickets that we would give to the driver of the car and solving them of any blame and any liability and tell them who we are and that kind of thing.
So it made the driver feel better about it.
I've hitchhiked all over this state.
All right, if you were hitchhiking from Beaumont, where was the best place to catch the ride?
You'd go out 290, I mean Highway 90, toward Houston at Amelia, which in that day was about four or five miles out of town.
And after Highway 105 got to be improved from being just a logging road, 105 was a good place to go.
You'd go about...
four or five miles north of town, where 105 came into 69, and 105 would bring you right into Navasota, and then you'd get on Highway 6 and come up here.
Was there a special, and I don't know the answer to this one, was there kind of a specially good place in Houston to get a ride?
Was there a certain corner?
The Houston A&M Club would put up little shacks out on
Highway 90 and on Highway 290, right where Highway 6 would take off from Highway 90, there was a shack.
And that would keep you out of the weather.
And if I may spin this little yarn.
Please do.
My roommate, Walter Evans, and I were hitchhiking
This was when I was a freshman, he was a sophomore.
For some reason, Evans couldn't get a car off his dad's used car lot that weekend and we were having to hitchhike back late.
